<br>
I've started writing to a friend in Japan which is helping somewhat, but I would like to supplement that with reading as well.<br>
<br>
Any recommendations?  Manga would be nice since I could probably find translations online to compare to, but other sources are good too if you've had success with them.  I've tried reading some of the online newspapers like the daily yomiuri, but that was way too difficult for me right now, so I need to start lower and work my way up (something with less kanji).<br>
<br>
I've heard that DragonBall was fairly easy to translate and read, but honestly, although I like it I'm not that big a fan.  I may start with that though since it would be easy to find translations online to compare to.  <br>
<br>
I also heard that Kodomo no Omocha was fairly easy to work with, but it seems to me that it has a lot of cultural references that would probably just end up confusing me as I read.  <br>
<br>
Thanks for any thoughts you can give. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/18/03 11:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1095.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Reading material</span><hr size=1> hey dynamite,<br>
<br>
i believe if you look hard enough, you can find 'bilingual' manga, which feature the original japanese with english translations off to the side.  I'm not sure exactly where they are sold (I know <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.jlist.com" target="top">jlist</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> or <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.crosstoy.com" target="top">crosstoy</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> occasionally has some in stock), but you should be able to find online retailers without too much trouble.  This seems like it might be quite helpful for you.  Also, if I'm not mistaken, often these have the hiragana for some of the more complex kanji written in.<br>
<br>
Other than that, the pen pal is a good idea, as would be textbooks, if you feel up to it.  If you want to avoid textbooks, I think the manga idea you mentioned is great.<br>
<br>
Good luck on your studies!!<br>
<br>
